<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<chapter xml:id="ch-15-punctuation" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Punctuation</title>

  <objectives>
    <title>Learning Objectives</title>
    <ul>
      <li><p>Use commas correctly in compound and complex sentences</p></li>
      <li><p>Apply semicolons and colons appropriately</p></li>
      <li><p>Use apostrophes for possession and contractions</p></li>
      <li><p>Employ dashes and parentheses for emphasis and supplementary information</p></li>
      <li><p>Understand quotation mark conventions</p></li>
      <li><p>Apply punctuation rules consistently</p></li>
      <li><p>Comma</p></li>
      <li><p>Semicolon</p></li>
      <li><p>Colon</p></li>
      <li><p>Apostrophe</p></li>
      <li><p>Dash</p></li>
      <li><p>Parentheses</p></li>
      <li><p>Quotation marks</p></li>
      <li><p>Terminal punctuation</p></li>
      <li><p></p></li>
    </ul>
  </objectives>

  <p>Every chapter in this book has been about structure: the internal structure of words, the structure of phrases, the structure of clauses, the structure of sentences. This chapter asks a different question—not how grammatical structure works, but how it is represented on the page. Punctuation is the visual system that encodes grammatical relationships in writing. Every mark you place corresponds to something real in the grammar: a boundary between clauses, a distinction between restrictive and nonrestrictive modifiers, a relationship between a proposition and an elaboration. Students who understand grammar have a foundation for understanding punctuation that rule-memorizers do not: they can reason from structure rather than guess from habit.</p>

  <p>The marks covered here range from the universal (periods end sentences) to the nuanced (commas with nonrestrictive modifiers reflect the grammar of modification). As you work through this chapter, notice how often a punctuation rule is really a grammar rule in disguise. The rule about comma splices, for instance, is just the observation that two independent clauses are two independent clauses—and joining them requires more than a comma. The rule about commas with nonrestrictive relative clauses follows directly from the restrictive/nonrestrictive distinction you studied in Chapter 13. Punctuation and grammar are not separate subjects; they are the same subject viewed from two angles.</p>

  <section xml:id="ch-15-punctuation-sec-151">
    <title>The Purpose of Punctuation</title>

    <p>Punctuation marks are visual signals that clarify meaning and guide readers through text. They indicate pauses, separate elements, and show relationships between parts of sentences.</p>

    <p>Good punctuation makes prose easier to read and prevents misunderstanding:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p><foreign>Let's eat grandma.</foreign> (disturbing)</p></li>
      <li><p><foreign>Let's eat, grandma.</foreign> (dinner invitation)</p></li>
    </ul>

  </section>

  <section xml:id="ch-15-punctuation-sec-152">
    <title>Terminal Punctuation</title>

    <p>Every sentence in written English ends with one of three marks, and the choice among them is not arbitrary—it reflects the grammatical type of the sentence. You have already studied sentence types in Chapter 8: declarative sentences make statements, interrogative sentences ask questions, and exclamatory sentences express strong emotion or emphasis. Terminal punctuation encodes exactly these distinctions. The period, question mark, and exclamation point are, in that sense, the written counterparts of the sentence-type distinctions your grammar already recognizes.</p>

    <paragraphs>
      <title>Period (.)</title>
    </paragraphs>

    <p>Ends declarative sentences and mild imperatives:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p><foreign>The meeting is at noon.</foreign></p></li>
      <li><p><foreign>Please close the door.</foreign></p></li>
    </ul>

    <paragraphs>
      <title>Question Mark (?)</title>
    </paragraphs>

    <p>Ends direct questions:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p><foreign>What time is it?</foreign></p></li>
      <li><p><foreign>Have you finished?</foreign></p></li>
    </ul>

    <p><em>Note</em>: Indirect questions take periods:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p><foreign>She asked what time it was.</foreign></p></li>
    </ul>

    <paragraphs>
      <title>Exclamation Point (!)</title>
    </paragraphs>

    <p>Indicates strong emotion or emphasis:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p><foreign>Watch out!</foreign></p></li>
      <li><p><foreign>What a surprise!</foreign></p></li>
    </ul>

    <p>Use sparingly in formal writing.</p>

  </section>

  <section xml:id="ch-15-punctuation-sec-153">
    <title>The Comma</title>

    <p>The comma is the most frequently used—and misused—punctuation mark.</p>

    <p>Most comma errors come from treating the comma as a breathing mark—a place to pause—rather than as a grammatical signal. The truth is that every major comma rule corresponds to a structural boundary you can identify. A comma before a coordinating conjunction signals that two independent clauses are being joined. A comma after an introductory element signals that an adverbial or other fronted constituent has ended and the main clause is beginning. Commas around a relative clause signal that it is nonrestrictive—adding extra information rather than restricting reference. Once you can see these grammatical boundaries, comma placement becomes a matter of analysis rather than intuition. The rules below are organized by the structural context they respond to.</p>

    <paragraphs>
      <title>Comma in Compound Sentences</title>
    </paragraphs>

    <p>Place a comma before a coordinating conjunction joining independent clauses:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p><foreign>The sun set, <em>and</em> the stars appeared.</foreign></p></li>
      <li><p><foreign>She tried hard, <em>but</em> she didn't succeed.</foreign></p></li>
    </ul>

    <paragraphs>
      <title>Comma After Introductory Elements</title>
    </paragraphs>

    <p>Use a comma after introductory phrases or clauses:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p><foreign>After the meeting, we went to lunch.</foreign></p></li>
      <li><p><foreign>However, I disagree.</foreign></p></li>
      <li><p><foreign>Running quickly, she caught the bus.</foreign></p></li>
    </ul>

    <paragraphs>
      <title>Commas with Nonrestrictive Elements</title>
    </paragraphs>

    <p>In Chapter 13 you learned the distinction between restrictive and nonrestrictive modifiers. That distinction does real grammatical work, and commas are how writing marks it. A restrictive modifier identifies which member of a group the noun phrase refers to—removing it would change the meaning of the sentence. A nonrestrictive modifier adds supplementary information about a noun phrase whose reference is already established—removing it leaves the core meaning intact. Commas signal to the reader: <em>what follows is extra information, not identification</em>.</p>

    <p>Set off nonrestrictive (non-essential) modifiers with commas:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p><foreign>My sister, <em>who lives in Boston</em>, is visiting.</foreign></p></li>
      <li><p><foreign>The report, <em>which I submitted yesterday</em>, was approved.</foreign></p></li>
    </ul>

    <p><em>Do not</em> use commas with restrictive (essential) modifiers:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p><foreign>The students who studied passed.</foreign> (no commas—specifies which students)</p></li>
    </ul>

    <paragraphs>
      <title>Commas in Series</title>
    </paragraphs>

    <p>Separate items in a list:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p><foreign>She bought apples, oranges, and bananas.</foreign></p></li>
    </ul>

    <p>The comma before <foreign>and</foreign> (the <term>Oxford comma</term>) is optional but recommended for clarity:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p><foreign>I admire my parents, Gandhi, and Mother Teresa.</foreign> (clear)</p></li>
      <li><p><foreign>I admire my parents, Gandhi and Mother Teresa.</foreign> (ambiguous)</p></li>
    </ul>

    <paragraphs>
      <title>Commas with Coordinate Adjectives</title>
    </paragraphs>

    <p>Separate adjectives that independently modify the noun:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p><foreign>a tall, elegant woman</foreign> (<foreign>tall</foreign> and <foreign>elegant</foreign> both modify <foreign>woman</foreign>)</p></li>
    </ul>

    <p><em>Test</em>: If you can put <foreign>and</foreign> between them, use a comma.</p>

    <p><em>Don't</em> use commas between cumulative adjectives:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p><foreign>a big red barn</foreign> (not <foreign><delete>big, red barn</delete></foreign>—<foreign>big red</foreign> modifies <foreign>barn</foreign> together)</p></li>
    </ul>

    <paragraphs>
      <title>Comma Misuse</title>
    </paragraphs>

    <p><term>Comma splice</term>: Using only a comma between independent clauses:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p><foreign><delete>The rain stopped, we went outside.</delete></foreign></p></li>
      <li><p>Correct: <foreign>The rain stopped, and we went outside.</foreign></p></li>
    </ul>

    <p><em>Separating subject from verb</em>:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p><foreign><delete>The man who arrived late, was my cousin.</delete></foreign></p></li>
      <li><p>Correct: <foreign>The man who arrived late was my cousin.</foreign></p></li>
    </ul>

  </section>

  <section xml:id="ch-15-punctuation-sec-154">
    <title>The Semicolon</title>

    <p>The semicolon occupies an interesting position in the punctuation system: it is stronger than a comma but weaker than a period. Grammatically, it signals that two independent clauses are closely related in meaning—so related that the writer wants to present them as a single unit rather than two separate sentences—but without the explicit logical connector that a coordinating conjunction like <foreign>and</foreign> or <foreign>but</foreign> would provide. Think of it as the written equivalent of a very short pause between two complete thoughts that belong together. Understanding what an independent clause is, which you studied in Chapter 8, is the key to using semicolons correctly.</p>

    <paragraphs>
      <title>Between Independent Clauses</title>
    </paragraphs>

    <p>Joins related independent clauses without a conjunction:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p><foreign>The rain stopped; we went outside.</foreign></p></li>
      <li><p><foreign>She's talented; however, she lacks experience.</foreign></p></li>
    </ul>

    <paragraphs>
      <title>In Complex Series</title>
    </paragraphs>

    <p>Separates items in a series when items contain commas:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p><foreign>The committee includes Dr. Smith, president; Mr. Jones, treasurer; and Ms. Lee, secretary.</foreign></p></li>
    </ul>

  </section>

  <section xml:id="ch-15-punctuation-sec-155">
    <title>The Colon</title>

    <p>Where the semicolon connects two independent clauses of roughly equal weight, the colon establishes a directional relationship: what comes before it is a complete sentence that anticipates something, and what comes after it delivers that something—a list, an explanation, a restatement, or a clarification. The grammatical rule that governs the colon follows from this directional logic: the material before the colon must be a complete independent clause. If the clause is incomplete, the colon breaks the flow of a construction that should be uninterrupted.</p>

    <paragraphs>
      <title>Introducing Lists</title>
    </paragraphs>

    <p>Use a colon after a complete sentence to introduce a list:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p><foreign>Please bring the following items: a pen, a notebook, and a calculator.</foreign></p></li>
    </ul>

    <p><em>Don't</em> use a colon after an incomplete sentence:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p><foreign><delete>Please bring: a pen, a notebook, and a calculator.</delete></foreign></p></li>
      <li><p>Correct: <foreign>Please bring a pen, a notebook, and a calculator.</foreign></p></li>
    </ul>

    <paragraphs>
      <title>Introducing Explanations</title>
    </paragraphs>

    <p>Use a colon to introduce an explanation or elaboration:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p><foreign>She had one goal: to finish her degree.</foreign></p></li>
      <li><p><foreign>The answer was clear: we needed more data.</foreign></p></li>
    </ul>

    <paragraphs>
      <title>In Formal Contexts</title>
    </paragraphs>

    <p>Between titles and subtitles:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p><foreign>Grammar Matters: A Guide to Standard English</foreign></p></li>
    </ul>

    <p>After salutations in formal letters:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p><foreign>Dear Dr. Smith:</foreign></p></li>
    </ul>

  </section>

  <section xml:id="ch-15-punctuation-sec-156">
    <title>The Apostrophe</title>

    <p>The apostrophe has two grammatically distinct jobs, and keeping them separate is the key to using it correctly. Its first job is to mark <em>possession</em>—the genitive relationship between a noun and whatever follows it. Recall from Chapter 5 that English has two ways to express this relationship: a prepositional phrase (<foreign>the tail of the dog</foreign>) and the Saxon genitive, which uses an apostrophe-s inflection (<foreign>the dog's tail</foreign>). The apostrophe in that construction is not decorative; it marks a real morphological operation. The apostrophe's second job is to signal <em>contraction</em>—the omission of one or more letters when two words are reduced to one. These two uses are unrelated to each other, but they share the same punctuation mark, which is why apostrophe errors are so common.</p>

    <paragraphs>
      <title>Possession</title>
    </paragraphs>

    <p>Singular nouns: Add <foreign>'s</foreign></p>

    <ul>
      <li><p><foreign>the dog's tail</foreign></p></li>
      <li><p><foreign>James's book</foreign> (or <foreign>James' book</foreign>)</p></li>
    </ul>

    <p>Plural nouns ending in <foreign>-s</foreign>: Add <foreign>'</foreign></p>

    <ul>
      <li><p><foreign>the dogs' tails</foreign></p></li>
      <li><p><foreign>the students' grades</foreign></p></li>
    </ul>

    <p>Plural nouns not ending in <foreign>-s</foreign>: Add <foreign>'s</foreign></p>

    <ul>
      <li><p><foreign>the children's toys</foreign></p></li>
      <li><p><foreign>the women's team</foreign></p></li>
    </ul>

    <paragraphs>
      <title>Contractions</title>
    </paragraphs>

    <p>Apostrophes replace omitted letters:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p><foreign>don't</foreign> (<foreign>do not</foreign>)</p></li>
      <li><p><foreign>it's</foreign> (<foreign>it is</foreign>)</p></li>
      <li><p><foreign>they're</foreign> (<foreign>they are</foreign>)</p></li>
    </ul>

    <paragraphs>
      <title>Common Errors</title>
    </paragraphs>

    <p><foreign>Its</foreign> vs. <foreign>It's</foreign>:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p><foreign>Its</foreign> = possessive (<foreign>The dog wagged its tail.</foreign>)</p></li>
      <li><p><foreign>It's</foreign> = <foreign>it is</foreign> (<foreign>It's raining.</foreign>)</p></li>
    </ul>

    <p><foreign>Their</foreign>, <foreign>There</foreign>, <foreign>They're</foreign>:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p><foreign>Their</foreign> = possessive (<foreign>Their house</foreign>)</p></li>
      <li><p><foreign>There</foreign> = location (<foreign>over there</foreign>)</p></li>
      <li><p><foreign>They're</foreign> = <foreign>they are</foreign> (<foreign>They're coming</foreign>)</p></li>
    </ul>

  </section>

  <section xml:id="ch-15-punctuation-sec-157">
    <title>Dashes and Parentheses</title>

    <p>Both dashes and parentheses allow a writer to insert supplementary material into a sentence without making it a separate sentence. Grammatically, they solve the same problem: how do you include information that is relevant but not central to the main clause? The difference between them is one of emphasis and tone. Dashes are loud—they signal an interruption, an aside delivered with energy. Parentheses are quiet; they whisper supplementary information to the reader while the main clause continues on its way. Commas can serve the same function with nonrestrictive elements, so the choice among commas, dashes, and parentheses is partly stylistic, but the grammatical function is consistent across all three.</p>

    <paragraphs>
      <title>Em Dash (—)</title>
    </paragraphs>

    <p>Sets off emphatic or interrupting material:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p><foreign>The answer—surprisingly—was yes.</foreign></p></li>
      <li><p><foreign>She had one goal—and only one—to succeed.</foreign></p></li>
    </ul>

    <p>Creates stronger emphasis than commas.</p>

    <paragraphs>
      <title>En Dash (–)</title>
    </paragraphs>

    <p>Indicates ranges:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p><foreign>pages 10–20</foreign></p></li>
      <li><p><foreign>the 2020–2021 academic year</foreign></p></li>
    </ul>

    <paragraphs>
      <title>Parentheses ( )</title>
    </paragraphs>

    <p>Enclose supplementary or explanatory material:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p><foreign>The results (see Table 3) were significant.</foreign></p></li>
      <li><p><foreign>She graduated in 2010 (the same year I started).</foreign></p></li>
    </ul>

    <p>Creates less emphasis than dashes.</p>

  </section>

  <section xml:id="ch-15-punctuation-sec-158">
    <title>Quotation Marks</title>

    <p>Quotation marks flag a special relationship between a piece of language and the text that contains it. When you quote someone directly, you are reporting their exact words rather than paraphrasing them—the quotation marks signal that the words inside belong to another speaker or writer, not to you. This is grammatically significant: you saw in Chapter 14 that English can embed speech both as a that-clause (<foreign>She said that she would come</foreign>, an indirect quotation with no quotation marks) and as a direct quotation (<foreign>She said, "I will come"</foreign>, where the original words are preserved). The choice between direct and indirect quotation changes the grammar of the sentence, and quotation marks are the written marker of the direct form.</p>

    <paragraphs>
      <title>Direct Quotations</title>
    </paragraphs>

    <p>Enclose exact words:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p><foreign>She said, "I'll be there."</foreign></p></li>
      <li><p><foreign>"I'll be there," she said.</foreign></p></li>
    </ul>

    <paragraphs>
      <title>Titles</title>
    </paragraphs>

    <p>Use for shorter works (articles, chapters, poems, songs):</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p><foreign>I read "The Road Not Taken."</foreign></p></li>
    </ul>

    <paragraphs>
      <title>Punctuation with Quotation Marks</title>
    </paragraphs>

    <p><em>American convention</em>: Periods and commas inside quotation marks:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p><foreign>She said, "I agree."</foreign></p></li>
      <li><p><foreign>He called it "amazing," but I disagreed.</foreign></p></li>
    </ul>

    <p><em>British convention</em>: Periods and commas may go outside if not part of the quotation.</p>

    <p>Question marks and exclamation points depend on the quotation:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p><foreign>Did she say "yes"?</foreign> (question is mine)</p></li>
      <li><p><foreign>She asked, "Are you coming?"</foreign> (question is hers)</p></li>
    </ul>

  </section>

    <section xml:id="ch-15-homework">
    <title>Homework: Punctuation</title>

    <subsection>
      <title>Part 1: Comma Usage (approx. 10 minutes)</title>

      <paragraphs>
        <title>Instructions</title>
      </paragraphs>
      <p>Add commas where needed in each sentence and briefly explain the function of each comma you add (compound sentence, introductory element, series, nonrestrictive modifier, coordinate adjectives, etc.).</p>

      <paragraphs>
        <title>Example (completed)</title>
      </paragraphs>

      <p><foreign>After the meeting ended we discussed the proposal.</foreign></p>

      <p>Corrected: <foreign>After the meeting ended, we discussed the proposal.</foreign></p>

      <p>Function: comma after introductory adverb clause</p>

      <paragraphs>
        <title>Exercises</title>
      </paragraphs>

      <p><em>Exercise 1.</em> <foreign>When the storm passed we surveyed the damage and began cleanup efforts.</foreign></p>

      <p>Corrected:</p>
      <p>Function(s):</p>

      <p><em>Exercise 2.</em> <foreign>She is talented hardworking and creative.</foreign></p>

      <p>Corrected:</p>
      <p>Function(s):</p>

      <p><em>Exercise 3.</em> <foreign>My brother who lives in Seattle is visiting next week.</foreign></p>

      <p>Corrected:</p>
      <p>Function(s):</p>

      <p><em>Exercise 4.</em> <foreign>The meeting was productive but it ran overtime.</foreign></p>

      <p>Corrected:</p>
      <p>Function(s):</p>

      <p><em>Exercise 5.</em> <foreign>The tall distinguished professor gave an inspiring lecture.</foreign></p>

      <p>Corrected:</p>
      <p>Function(s):</p>

      <p><em>Exercise 6.</em> Explain why the following sentence does NOT need a comma:</p>

      <p><foreign>The students who completed the assignment received extra credit.</foreign></p>

      <p>Explanation:</p>
    </subsection>

    <subsection>
      <title>Part 2: Semicolons and Colons (approx. 5 minutes)</title>

      <paragraphs>
        <title>Instructions</title>
      </paragraphs>
      <p>Choose the correct punctuation mark (colon or semicolon) for each sentence and explain your reasoning.</p>

      <paragraphs>
        <title>Example (completed)</title>
      </paragraphs>

      <p><foreign>She had three goals ( : / ; ) to finish her degree, to find a job, and to buy a house.</foreign></p>

      <p>Choice: colon</p>

      <p>Reasoning: A colon introduces a list after a complete sentence.</p>

      <paragraphs>
        <title>Exercises</title>
      </paragraphs>

      <p><em>Exercise 7.</em> <foreign>She had one goal ( : / ; ) to finish the project on time.</foreign></p>

      <p>Choice:</p>
      <p>Reasoning:</p>

      <p><em>Exercise 8.</em> <foreign>The rain stopped ( : / ; ) we went outside immediately.</foreign></p>

      <p>Choice:</p>
      <p>Reasoning:</p>

      <p><em>Exercise 9.</em> <foreign>The committee includes three officers ( : / ; ) Dr. Lee, president; Ms. Park, secretary; and Mr. Kim, treasurer.</foreign></p>

      <p>Choice:</p>
      <p>Reasoning:</p>

      <p><em>Exercise 10.</em> <foreign>He was exhausted ( : / ; ) however, he continued working.</foreign></p>

      <p>Choice:</p>
      <p>Reasoning:</p>
    </subsection>

    <subsection>
      <title>Part 3: Apostrophes (approx. 5 minutes)</title>

      <paragraphs>
        <title>Instructions</title>
      </paragraphs>
      <p>Correct any apostrophe errors in each sentence.</p>

      <paragraphs>
        <title>Example (completed)</title>
      </paragraphs>

      <p><foreign>The dogs tail was wagging.</foreign></p>

      <p>Corrected: <foreign>The dog's tail was wagging.</foreign></p>

      <paragraphs>
        <title>Exercises</title>
      </paragraphs>

      <p><em>Exercise 11.</em> <foreign>Its important to understand its function in the sentence.</foreign></p>

      <p>Corrected:</p>

      <p><em>Exercise 12.</em> <foreign>The students books were left in the classroom.</foreign></p>

      <p>Corrected:</p>

      <p><em>Exercise 13.</em> <foreign>The Joneses car is parked in the driveway.</foreign></p>

      <p>Corrected:</p>

      <p><em>Exercise 14.</em> <foreign>Theyre going to their house over there.</foreign></p>

      <p>Corrected:</p>

      <p><em>Exercise 15.</em> <foreign>The womens team won the championship.</foreign></p>

      <p>Corrected:</p>
    </subsection>

    <subsection>
      <title>Part 4: Comprehensive Punctuation (approx. 10 minutes)</title>

      <paragraphs>
        <title>Instructions</title>
      </paragraphs>
      <p>Add all necessary punctuation to the following passages.</p>

      <paragraphs>
        <title>Example (completed)</title>
      </paragraphs>

      <p>Unpunctuated: <foreign>When she arrived the meeting had already started however no one seemed to mind</foreign></p>

      <p>Punctuated: <foreign>When she arrived, the meeting had already started; however, no one seemed to mind.</foreign></p>

      <paragraphs>
        <title>Exercises</title>
      </paragraphs>

      <p><em>Exercise 16.</em> <foreign>When the meeting ended the participants left quickly however several stayed behind to discuss the proposal the main question was this should they proceed</foreign></p>

      <p>Punctuated:</p>

      <p><em>Exercise 17.</em> <foreign>The report which took three months to complete contained the following recommendations reduce costs improve efficiency and increase employee training however the board rejected all three proposals</foreign></p>

      <p>Punctuated:</p>

      <p><em>Exercise 18.</em> <foreign>Dr Smith who has been teaching for twenty years said I believe that students learn best when theyre engaged in meaningful activities</foreign></p>

      <p>Punctuated:</p>
    </subsection>

    <subsection>
      <title>Part 5: Analysis and Application (approx. 10 minutes)</title>

      <paragraphs>
        <title>Instructions</title>
      </paragraphs>
      <p>Answer the following questions about punctuation.</p>

      <paragraphs>
        <title>Meaning and Punctuation</title>
      </paragraphs>

      <paragraphs>
        <title>Exercises</title>
      </paragraphs>

      <p><em>Exercise 19.</em> The following sentences are punctuated differently. Explain how the meaning changes:</p>

      <p>a) <foreign>The students who studied passed the exam.</foreign></p>

      <p>b) <foreign>The students, who studied, passed the exam.</foreign></p>

      <p>Explanation of (a):</p>

      <p>Explanation of (b):</p>

      <p>How does punctuation change the meaning?</p>

      <paragraphs>
        <title>Real-World Application</title>
      </paragraphs>

      <p><em>Exercise 20.</em> Find or create a paragraph of 3-4 sentences. Identify at least four different punctuation marks and explain the grammatical reason for each.</p>

      <p>Paragraph:</p>

      <p>Punctuation mark 1:</p>
      <p>Reason:</p>

      <p>Punctuation mark 2:</p>
      <p>Reason:</p>

      <p>Punctuation mark 3:</p>
      <p>Reason:</p>

      <p>Punctuation mark 4:</p>
      <p>Reason:</p>

      <paragraphs>
        <title>Reflection</title>
      </paragraphs>

      <p><em>Exercise 21.</em> Answer the following questions:</p>

      <p>a) What punctuation rule do you find most confusing or difficult to apply consistently?</p>

      <p>b) Why do you think this rule is challenging?</p>

      <p>c) What strategy might help you master it?</p>
    </subsection>

    <p><em>Total estimated time: 40 minutes</em></p>
  </section>

  <glossary>
    <title>Glossary</title>
    <gi>
      <title>Comma splice</title>
      <p>The error of joining independent clauses with only a comma.</p>
    </gi>
    <gi>
      <title>Nonrestrictive element</title>
      <p>A modifier that adds extra information; set off with commas.</p>
    </gi>
    <gi>
      <title>Oxford comma</title>
      <p>The comma before <foreign>and</foreign> in a series.</p>
    </gi>
    <gi>
      <title>Restrictive element</title>
      <p>A modifier essential for identification; no commas.</p>
    </gi>
    <gi>
      <title>Terminal punctuation</title>
      <p>Punctuation that ends sentences (period, question mark, exclamation point).</p>
    </gi>
  </glossary>

</chapter>
